older-102"></div><p class=3D"question"><em>- What is the plus and minus gra=
ding scale and how does it affect my GPA?</em></p><p>This is a question I'm=
 often asked by students, so I have written a short paper to demonstrate ho=
w I determine minimum percentages when using the plus and minus grading sca=
le.</p><picture><source type=3D"image/webp" srcset=3D"/public/images/bens-p=
hoto.jpg"><source type=3D"image/jpeg" srcset=3D"/public/images/bens-photo.j=
pg"><img src=3D"https://www.thegradecalculator.com/public/images/bens-photo=
.jpg" class=3D"profile" alt=3D"ben picture"></picture><h1 class=3D"section-=
title">Using the Plus and Minus Grading Scale</h1><span>By <a href=3D"http:=
//www.benegg.net/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer">Ben Eggleston</a></=
span><div id=3D"section-one" class=3D"container"><div><h1 class=3D"subtitle=
">The Problem</h1><p>In the Fall 2008 semester, the College of Liberal Arts=
 and Sciences added grades with pluses and minuses (A=E2=80=93, B+, etc.) t=
o its list of available grades. (Such grades had been available in some sch=
ools at KU previously, but not in the College.) Here are the web pages stat=
ing the KU and CLAS grade lists:<br><a href=3D"http://www.registrar.ku.edu/=
~registr/transcript/overview.shtml">http://www.registrar.ku.edu/~registr/tr=
anscript/overview.shtml</a> <a href=3D"http://www.collegesas.ku.edu/policie=
s/GPA.shtml">http://www.collegesas.ku.edu/policies/GPA.shtml</a></p><p>When=
 the only grades were A, B, C, D, and F, it was pretty easy to come up with=
 a final grade calculator, and it was easy for me to show students how to c=
alculate grade percentage. For example, I usually used the following gradin=
g scale:</p><table class=3D"table"><tbody><tr><th colspan=3D"2"><span>Table=
 1:</span></th></tr><tr><td><span>letter grade</span></td><td><span>minimum=
 percentage</span></td></tr><tr><td><span>A</span></td><td><span>90</span><=
/td></tr><tr><td><span>B</span></td><td><span>80</span></td></tr><tr><td><s=
pan>C</span></td><td><span>70</span></td></tr><tr><td><span>D</span></td><t=
d><span>60</span></td></tr><tr><td><span>F</span></td><td><span>=E2=80=94</=
span></td></tr></tbody></table><p>With the introduction of pluses and minus=
es, minimum percentages need to be determined for a much longer list of gra=
des, as shown in table 2. (For now I=E2=80=99ll assume the possibility of A=
+, even though it is not an available grade at KU, and then I=E2=80=99ll ad=
just for its absence at the end.)</p><table class=3D"table"><tbody><tr><th =
colspan=3D"2"><span>Table 2:</span></th></tr><tr><td><span>letter grade</sp=
an></td><td><span>minimum percentage</span></td></tr><tr><td><span>A+</span=
></td><td><span>?</span></td></tr><tr><td><span>A</span></td><td><span>?</s=
pan></td></tr><tr><td><span>A-</span></td><td><span>?</span></td></tr><tr><=
td><span>B+</span></td><td><span>?</span></td></tr><tr><td><span>B</span></=
td><td><span>?</span></td></tr><tr><td><span>B-</span></td><td><span>?</spa=
n></td></tr><tr><td><span>C+</span></td><td><span>?</span></td></tr><tr><td=
><span>C</span></td><td><span>?</span></td></tr><tr><td><span>C-</span></td=
><td><span>?</span></td></tr><tr><td><span>D+</span></td><td><span>?</span>=
</td></tr><tr><td><span>D</span></td><td><span>?</span></td></tr><tr><td><s=
pan>D-</span></td><td><span>?</span></td></tr><tr><td><span>F</span></td><t=
d><span>=E2=80=94</span></td></tr></tbody></table></div><div><h1 class=3D"s=
ubtitle">My Solution</h1><p>If you think of the new grading scale as dividi=
ng each of the old grades=E2=80=99 ranges into three smaller ranges (e.g., =
the A range gets divided into ranges for A+, A, and A=E2=80=93), it seems l=
ogical to think that the minimum percentage for an A=E2=80=93 under my new =
grading scale should be the same as the minimum percentage for an A under m=
y old grading scale, that the minimum percentage for a B=E2=80=93 under my =
new grading scale should be the same as the minimum percentage for a B unde=
r my old grading scale, and so on. So I can partially fill in my table as f=
ollows:</p><table class=3D"table"><tbody><tr><th colspan=3D"2"><span>Table =
3:</span></th></tr><tr><td><span>letter grade</span></td><td><span>minimum =
percentage</span></td></tr><tr><td><span>A+</span></td><td><span>?</span></=
td></tr><tr><td><span>A</span></td><td><span>?</span></td></tr><tr><td><spa=
n>A-</span></td><td><span>90</span></td></tr><tr><td><span>B+</span></td><t=
